I think I waited 15 minutes for this first photo. Learning from one of the best, to be patient and sit in the chaos and wait for the moment to present itself. I sat and sat, waiting for the handoff before it finally came. A blur of photos to catch not one, but both boats handing off food at the same time. 

Knowing I wouldn’t have a large window, I cranked my shutter speed to ensure I’d get a clean photo. Luckily the light allowed for the fast shutter and all worked out.

Went to the Dolomites only knowing one person. Ended up bumping into a handful of other people that by chance became excellent models / subjects. Niclas let me shoot the crap out of him the entire time, which was good for my adventure photography style and practice. We bumped into other hikers who were happy to strike a pose so I could get a shot or two! @mountainkimbo was running down the ramp while I was testing the air with the Mini 3 pro by @djiglobal . Also bumped into a lady and her fiancé doing an engagement shoot. Her photographer was happy to let me snag a couple photos of her striking dress against the mountains, a rarity for this part of the world. Got some awesome photos of myself as well. Something you wouldn’t expect from a hiking trip. All in all, I guess the takeaway is- you can’t really rule anything out when you travel.

“The body moves in the direction the head is facing”

Just one of the many bits of wisdom that @drewtravels4life shared on the @luidiazpodcast this week. 

Whether referencing a quote from his mom, sharing embarrassing stories about a failed astro shoots, or paying respect to his peers, teachers and heroes in modern day photography circles like @niclasglud or @emmett_sparling Drew is just the guy you need to listen to, to not only realise that what you want is totally achievable, but also that it won’t take radical or all-in gestures or actions to make it so.

ENJOY!

And please like, follow, share and connect with any of us ☝️ to find out more about our work 😊🙏

In this episode of the @luidiazpodcast - @drewtravels4life talks about the beauty of collaboration and how it often leads to surprise outcomes, happy accidents and  great adventures like the adventure he and good friend @niclasglud had at the Dolomites while hunting for the perfect shot.

Talking to Drew is like a dream. You sit there listening to someone who’s living the journey, who’s in the thick of it, who’s evolving right before your eyes and has the presence of mind to be able to recognise the wonderful serendipitous moments that go hand in hand with being in the process of living your dream ✨

THANKS TO EVERYONE that has enjoyed the podcast so far and sent amazing messages of support 🙏

If you love what you hear, please like, follow, share, leave a review on Apple or Spotify and connect with any of us ☝️ to find out more about our work 😊🙏

Instagram threw together this cool recap for the year. Figured I’d get on the trend and throw up some of my funny selfies throughout the year. It’s been a fun year with tons of ups and downs, but overall it was a good year. Met some amazing people and went on some amazing adventures. Added a few new countries to my list, and visited some old favorites. From winter and spring in the French alps, to summer in Europe. Getting to visit Panamá and Belize late summer, to fall in the Dolomites of Italy and Turkey, WOW. I couldn’t be more grateful for the amazing opportunities I’ve received to travel this much this year. I’m excited to start the year off with a bang, and be traveling for New Years! Going to follow it up, by immediately going to India for nearly a month in late February! We’re not slowing down!! Let’s go!!!!

This particular day in the Dolomites was supposed to be the worst weather of the trip. Rain and overcast nonstop. 

At this point we had woken up every day at 4am or earlier for sunrise hikes, for the entire previous week. Sleeping in sounded amazing, but we convinced ourselves to go big or go home, and go out and see if we could make something of the overcast. Well… we found this insane cloud inversion down in the valley. We chased it for probably an hour until it stabilized and we were able to fly our drones up through it. It was my first time ever seeing a cloud inversion like this in person. Unreal experience, and follows the moral of the story, which is “you miss, 100% of the chances you don’t take”. ⁣

Today I went to the docks of the southern shores of Kauai. The goal was to get on a charter boat and sail along the Napali coast. 

Nearly 5 hours of exploring and I was able to come away with some photos like this! I pulled a couple off the card tonight just to give you guys a little teaser of more to come. 

Traveler’s tip - swells in the winters of Hawaii are very high, so if you are one that gets sea sick, you should do this in the summer instead.

The Napali Coast is easily one of the most strikingly beautiful landscapes on the islands of Hawaii. Located on the northern shore of Kauai - it’s largely inaccessible. If you want to get shots like this, it’s best to take a local tour boat or helicopter. I did both over the course of 2 days, to explore the coastline fully. 

I recommend booking a boat as close to sunset as possible to ensure you get golden glows like this!

Lesson from this reel - speak with locals. Learn from those around you. So I’ve seen highway 3 on numerous instagram photos. It’s a famous photo from the air of the divided highway (raised bridge style) over a canon of trees. The only issue with highway 3 is that there are absolutely NO pull offs to get the drone in the air. The only access that I found was folks biking the highway on a peddle bike and flying from the shoulders.  I wasn’t down for that, so I drove through the tunnel at the end and was greeted with this on the backside of the mountains. Luckily sunset was still amazing on this side.

Traveler tip - go in the morning!! This canyon fills with clouds and mist around 12pm, and the views quickly disappear.

So this beach is pretty remarkable. The history with this coastline is that, rulers would appoint a climber to bring the remains of the dead Kings to these remote parts of the island. They were instructed to bury them where no one would find them, and then jump off the cliffs to their deaths to protect the location of the graves. This beach is known for similar events, and is highly protected. One can’t even park a boat on it. You must either fly above like this, or swim up to it from afar. ⁣

Kauai has one of those climates where things just grow 24/7. Doesn’t really seem to matter what time of year you visit, there’s always a lush jungle to greet you. Who keeps the jungle this pristine though? 

Did you know, that the majority of Kauai is actually owned by a handful of rich families? The land was purchased from Hawaiians decades ago (including an island which was traded for a few thousand dollars and a grand piano) and has been private land ever since. On one hand, it keeps the jungles untamed and wild, like this incredible waterfall… on the other hand, a very large portion of the island is actually inaccessible to Hawaiians, or people visiting. 

Should it be made accessible to all? Or should it stay private and closed to protect the ecosystem? 

Curious what you all think!  Enjoy the photos!

This was the first photo I took pulled over on the side of the road in the Dolomites trying Astro. The stars were SO bright I could see the milky way with my eyes. I was able to set up my crappy tripod and get the photo on the very first try. 

When shooting Astro - there’s a couple big things to do. 

1.) - try to shoot with a wider lens. Typically you want to be 12-24 mm wide. You can go more narrow, but it will possibly reduce how much of the Milky Way you get in a single photo. 

2 - you want to use the lowest aperture your lens allows. In this case my lens was at f2.8. This lets in the maximum amount of light. 

3 - you want to set your exposure based on your lens. The higher your MM, the shorter the exposure time to avoid star trails. For example - 24 mm - should be roughly 20-25 second exposure. 15mm can expose up to 30 seconds. Good rule of thumb is 25ish seconds. If you see star trails, just lower your exposure time and raise your iso. 

4.) - start with an iso of 100 and see how the photo looks. You can always raise it again if the photo is too dark. The goal is to use the least amount of ISO needed to get a bright image. Usually that will be somewhere in the 200-1000 range. 

Don’t be afraid to fire away and try different setting combos! 

Enjoy :)

So this valley in the Dolomites is one where you aren’t supposed to drive your car to, unless you are staying at one of the cabins. To make sure we were leaving a minimal footprint, @niclasglud and I hiked in from several miles away. We arrived well before sunrise in the pitch black, and trekked our way to the iconic alpine valley. After arriving and setting up, we heard engines coming down the small dirt road. Much to our surprise, vans full of tourists showed up and dropped off close to 30 or 40 people. They stumbled down the hill, and one lady literally walked around my shoulder and plopped her tripod down right in front of me. Just when I thought it couldn’t get any worse, she farted and didn’t bat an eye. She didn’t excuse herself or apologize or anything! I don’t know if it’s something from her country or culture that doesn’t care about that sort of thing, but wow! I was completely taken aback. 

I was happy to visit this valley, but unfortunately disappointed that local tourism companies have been breaking the rules to actively ruin an icon spot. 

I wanted to share this story with you guys because it’s important to know both sides to a photo. This valley is extremely famous now, largely because of instagram. It was, and should remain a hiking destination. You should pay your dues in the form of a long hike in the dark to see this spot at sunrise. Large vans or busses driving on these small local village roads is not ok. Let’s keep these areas as the pristine gardens we love them to be. 

#landscapephotography #travelphotography #dolomites #ecotourism #conservation #leavenotrace

The langur monkey is a species of Old World monkey that is native to South and Southeast Asia. It is one of the two types of monkeys that live in India, the other being the rhesus macaque. Langur monkeys are usually quite large, with adults reaching a length of up to three feet. They have a grey or black coat and long tails, and are known for their long, shaggy fur and white beards. The langur monkeys are also very social creatures and can be seen living in large groups of up to 50 individuals. They are highly intelligent and have been observed engaging in complex behaviors such as solving problems, using tools, and even displaying rudimentary forms of communication!

My first time seeing the Taj Mahal. It’s such an incredible structure that actually lives up to its reputation. It’s absolutely massive, and so perfectly symmetrical that it captures your gaze and refuses to let go. 

The Taj is a magnificent ivory-white marble mausoleum located in Agra, India. It was built by the Mughal emperor Shah Jahan in memory of his beloved wife Mumtaz Mahal, who died in childbirth in 1631. Construction of the Taj Mahal began in 1632 and took over 20 years to complete, with thousands of workers and artisans involved in its creation. The structure is renowned for its intricate architectural design, featuring minarets, domes, and arches adorned with intricate carvings and inlaid with precious stones. Today, the Taj Mahal is considered one of the most iconic and enduring symbols of love in the world.

Several months ago, I watched a Hulu documentary called “The Last Tourist”. To this day, it’s one of my all time favorites for shedding a light on how powerful a force tourism can be. Both good and bad. It highlighted many ways in which the West travels, that are both damaging local economies and suppressing the very cultures people want to visit. It also shined a light on some amazing people doing some amazing things. One such group, are these amazing Women at @sakhakiwomenwithwheels. 

Their goal is to bring empowerment to Women through access to safe and reliable employment. The Ladies over at Sakha learn to drive in the chaotic and challenging environments in India, where they easily carve out a slice of the economy that is usually dominated by men. Women empowering Women, and serving their fellow Women by offering transportation services to anyone wanting to feel safe while they navigate. 

I wanted to meet these amazing Ladies in person, so I reached out to them to offer them a free photo shoot. I wanted to help shed extra light on their amazing efforts and bring positive vibes to their cause. 

So - go check out their account @sakhakiwomenwithwheels 

Show them some love - and if you are ever traveling in India, please message them and use their services. It’s way more than a cab ride… it’s an incredible story of breaking the cycle of misogyny in a way that is sustainable for generations to come. 

#travelphotography #india #womensupportingwomen #womenempowerment #womeninbusiness #hulu

Some random photos of me working my way through Jaipur in India. ☺️🌎

#travelphotography #selfie #jaipur #india #travel

I’ll be totally honest with you guys about this city, and this building. It’s a bitter sweet love affair. The building and its grounds are completely magical. The story behind the Taj is special as well. A King who lost his wife, and built this incredible monument to her. So well thought out, that even the pillars are offset in such a way that in an earthquake, they would fall away from the main structure. 

On the flip side, the land, and the river around the Taj, is really rough. I’ve seen photos of the Taj from the river, and I even shot and posted on myself! The river side is so incredibly polluted that you have to spend an hour on photoshop trying to remove all the plastic from the shore and the water. 

I think I’m at the point now with social media that hyping up a place, and not showing both sides is completely against who I am as a person and as a photographer. 

Would I recommended the Taj? Absolutely, but be prepared for what’s outside the walls… 

#travelphotography #india #tajmahal #taj #igvsreality #traveldestinations #landscapephotography

Really remarkable to get to experience a deeper side of a culture when you connect with some of the people there.

Despite the riders attempting to hustle money from me for photos - I simply squared up and took my shots and moved on to continue exploring the beautiful grounds. 

The fort is well maintained, beautifully kept, and welcoming. I’d definitely recommend it!

These folks are tea vendors in Jaipur India. They earn an average of $200-$400 USD a month depending on business. When business is bad, they can earn as little as $5 or $6 a day.

In my broadcast channel, I created a poll asking if people thought it was ok if photographers posted more than once a day. Specifically, a reel and a photo series in the same day. 

When I travel it probably looks like I’m editing / shooting all the time, but really, I have a rather long backlog of photos that I need to edit. I don’t batch edit, or fly through edits for the sake of creating content or pushing it out quickly. Each photo gets attention to bring it to the beauty that I remember it as when I took the photo. 

Even still - I have found myself traveling more frequently and harder than ever before in my life. I turned 33 this year, and with it came in stark reminder that I’m not getting any younger and there’s a humongous world out there still left to visit.

Thank you all for voting on the poll! I’m going to post whenever the content arrives now instead of trying to only post once a day. If that means photos and reels in the same day, then cool. I hope you guys are enjoying the India photos! It was one of the craziest and coolest adventures I’ve had and I’m happy you all like the photos! 

#travelphotography #meaningfulstories #natgeo #natgeotravel #natgeowomenofimpact #traveldestinations #india #jaipur

The monkey temple in Rajasthan India is a pretty cool spot that attracts visitors from all over. Also known as the Galta Ji Temple, it's nestled in the Aravalli Hills and surrounded by natural springs and greenery. Hundreds of monkeys hang out there, and they're pretty chill with people - you can even feed them. The temple itself is pretty amazing, with some cool carvings and architecture. 

I busted out my new 85mm f1.2 to see how it handled the low light post sunset.. needless to say, it blew me away. What a lens!! 

What do you guys think of these little Rhesus Macaques? The females were so friendly! 

#travelphotography #india #monkeyseemonkeydo #rajasthan

This temple in Jaipur is called Galta Ji Temple or Hanuman Ji Temple, also affectionately called the ‘Monkey Temple’ of Jaipur by the locals. It was one of the absolute highlights of my entire trip. The temple grounds are overrun by hundreds of monkeys from the two primary species that live in India. At this spot, there’s also a beautiful spring water pond that feeds into the temple. The architecture is just gorgeous, and to top it off - it’s not well known, so it was nearly empty at sunset. Doesn’t get much better than that!

I got to chat with one of the holy men who lives there (he’s in the orange), and he told me to walk down a small hallway to his right. 

I went in, expecting maybe a statue or a pretty view… but wound up at the end of the hallway looking at a small fire being tended to by another monk. He gave me a blessing, and tied a small string around my wrist. I asked him about the fire, and he told me that it’s been burning unstopped for generations. Their job is to keep it going. 

Really incredible place. 

#landscapephotography #travelphotography #india #monkeys #templesofindia #temples

It’s a wonderful thing to know very little about a culture and to have it told to you by the locals of that culture. I didn’t know literally anything about Hinduism before I came to India. Not a thing, other than they had many different ways they they worshiped, and in many different forms. Seeing ancient temples, hearing the stories, listening to the people explain what they believe and why, is all part of my personal growth to be a better person, and a better traveler. Many folks find themselves content to stay within the confines of a nice hotel, rarely to leave its premises. You won’t find me with those folks though.  You’ll find me hanging out with this dude. Learning about 6000 years of history from his perspective. A small smile exchange as I walked away was all I needed to say goodbye for now, and see you next time. 

#travelphotography #india #traveldeeper #optoutside #portraitphotography #templesofindia

Got my little drone down into the base of the canyon - soaking up the raw beauty of Wailua Falls in Kauai. It's a sight that's hard to forget, especially if you're a fan of the TV show, Fantasy Island - yeah, this is the waterfall from the opening scene. When the sun hits it just right, a rainbow springs from the mist at the base of the falls. Now that's a postcard moment if I've ever seen one. The falls have a bit of a reputation - standing at 85 feet tall and dropping into a 30-foot deep pool. Ancient Hawaiians used to jump off it to prove their bravery, but I'd advise against it.

Getting here is a breeze, just a quick jaunt up Maalo Road and you're at a parking lot with a front-row seat to the falls. Fair warning though, like any good show, Wailua Falls is best when it's not trying too hard - a moderate flow is just right.

One of my first nights in India, @safariwithrohit and I were parked out on the balcony of my jungle lodge watching these incredible Langur monkeys playing in the golden light of sunset. 

At first I was worried it was a fleeting moment, so I let my dinner get cold while I sat photographing as many moments as possible. We soon realized though that the moment wasn’t fleeting, and they were all planning to play for over an hour in the sunset. We were able to pause, eat, have some cold beers, and take pictures at our leisure from the balcony as much as we wanted. 

To this day, the Langur sunset was probably my best experience with perfect monkey photography!

Last year my buddy @niclasglud hit me up and invited me to join him on a backpacking trip through the Dolomites. I couldn’t possibly say no. 

So I packed up warm clothes and more camera gear than I probably needed, and flew to Italy.

I arrived in Varanasi India, with little to know real idea what I was walking into. I had a general concept in my head, but it wasn’t nearly as tactile or stimulating as real life proved to be. 

On my first outing, I chose to bring my 85mm f1.2 lens because I was going to focus on telling the story of the PEOPLE of Varanasi. 

I made my way to the famous cremation fires, where bodies are burned 24/7 in what is considered one of the holiest places in all of India. To be cremated here is to bypass reincarnation and achieve nirvana in Hinduism. As such, people travel across the world to spend their final moments in Varanasi, and ultimately have their remains end up in the Ganges River. 

There are a group of caretakers who tend to the burning bodies on the banks of the river and sites known as “Ghats”. These people work night and day, keeping the fires burning, and performing the grim task of tidying up the fire as it burns through. As limbs fall, and things get disorganized, these men work to collect the pieces and return them to the fire to complete the cremation process. They also clean the site after, and ready fresh wood for the next. 

In years past, they were known as the “untouchables”. The Indian cast system was supposed to have been done away with, but speaking with many people in Varanasi revealed to me that they don’t believe it is truly gone. The untouchables are considered the lowest cast in Indian society, and as such, in this system, will never be able to lift out of a life of poverty and despair. 

I sat with this man for a few minutes and spoke with him. His English wasn’t the best, so his fellow fire keepers helped translate for me. I learned all I could, and asked to take his picture, before leaving a small gift and continuing the adventure in Varanasi, the city of Light.
